      <text>
        Kira woke to shifting light—the bioluminescence brightening gradually, like a sunrise but bluer. The vine walls of her quarters glowed softly, pulsing with a gentle rhythm—morning, probably.

        Scout was still there, settled near the entrance. (Scout bounces once—greeting or relief, hard to say.)

        Kira said, "Morning." Her voice was rough. (Scout bounces again—enthusiastic.)

        Buddy said, "Good morning, Kira. You slept for approximately nine hours. Vital signs are stable. Would you like a detailed sleep quality analysis?"

        Kira said, "No." She sat up carefully—her leg protested, still sore but manageable. The pain was different now—healing pain, not injury pain—progress.

        The facility was surprisingly quiet—just the faint rustle of the living walls breathing, and distant movement deeper in the structure.

        She had slept in an alien plant building on an alien planet, with a bouncing plant sphere as her companion. This was her life now.

        ¶

        Holloway said, "Good morning! Time for your daily health status update!" (Voice coming from a fruiting body sprouting near the doorway.)

        There it was—the routine.

        Kira took a breath. Kira said, "Good morning, Holloway. I'm ready to provide my daily health status update per wellness protocol." See? She was learning—phrase it in their language, use their frameworks; the forms came faster that way.

        Holloway said, "Excellent! How would you rate your overall wellness today on a scale of one to ten?"

        Kira said, "Seven. Injury site shows improvement. Pain level reduced from yesterday. Sleep quality was good." She stood, testing her leg—stiff but functional.

        Holloway said, "Wonderful! Any new symptoms or concerns to report?"

        Kira said, "Negative. No new symptoms."

        Holloway said, "Perfect. I'm documenting: overall wellness seven out of ten, injury improving, no new concerns." (Multiple fruiting bodies consult with each other.) Holloway continued, "Remedy will be here shortly for wound care assessment. Would you like me to update your care plan in the meantime?"

        Kira said, "Yes, please update my care plan." (She says yes because saying yes made things happen; saying no only generated more questions.)

        (Scout bounces approvingly.) The little plant had been there for every bureaucratic nightmare—nonverbal support that somehow helped more than Buddy's enthusiastic commentary.

        Mushrooms began fruiting in the corner—small pale clusters emerging rapidly from the soil.

        The robot arrived a minute later—movements still jerky but purposeful.

        Remedy said, "Good morning, Kira. Daily wound assessment protocol. How's the injury?"

        Kira said, "Better. Less pain, no signs of infection that I can see."

        Remedy said, "Let's verify that assessment—remove the bandage, please."

        Kira unwrapped the plant-fiber dressing. The wound beneath looked better—edges closed, redness reduced, no weeping. Chemistry was working.
      </text>
