        The robot examined it carefully, mechanical hands gentle.

        Remedy said, "Bacterial colonization successfully halted—cellular decomposition limited to damaged tissue only—that's good decomposition, the healing kind. New tissue formation progressing well. Your body is doing excellent work not dying."

        Kira said, "Thanks—I'm trying."

        Remedy said, "Very decomposable wound initially, but the antibacterial compounds prevented catastrophic tissue breakdown—human bodies are really quite remarkable at self-repair when we prevent the wrong kind of decomposition."

        Scout bounced sympathetically.

        Kira observed, "You're still talking about decomposition."

        Remedy said, "It's relevant! There's good decomposition—damaged cells breaking down so new ones can grow—and bad decomposition, which is bacteria eating you. We want one, not the other."

        Kira said, "I appreciate the distinction."

        Remedy applied fresh antibacterial gel—cool, slightly tingly—and said, "New bandage required. I'll need to document wound closure percentage, tissue regeneration status, and treatment efficacy rating."

        Of course—documentation.

        ¶

        Holloway called from the wall, "I have the wound assessment forms ready!"

        Forms—always forms.

        But Kira was learning this game too.

        Kira reported, "Wound closure approximately seventy percent—tissue regeneration visible—treatment efficacy highly effective."

        Holloway said, "Excellent self-assessment! Very thorough."

        Remedy applied fresh bandages—soft, clean, properly secured—and said, "You'll need daily wound care for another four to five days—then we can move to every other day—full healing maybe two weeks total."

        Two weeks—she could do two weeks. If rescue didn't come first—which seemed increasingly unlikely.

        Holloway said, "I'll note the updated care timeline. You're showing excellent progress, Kira—we're very pleased with your recovery trajectory!"

        Several fruiting bodies sprouted and consulted.

        They really were pleased—genuinely happy she wasn't dying. The warmth came through even in the bureaucratic language.

        Kira said, "Thank you—all of you. The treatment is working."

        Remedy said proudly, "*Chemistry doesn't lie!* Unlike bureaucracy, which is mostly lying to yourself that procedures solve everything."

        Holloway's fruiting bodies rustled—mild offense.

        Holloway countered, "Procedures provide structure and consistency—very important for coordinated care!"

        Remedy said, "*Structure is just organized lying.*"

        Scout bounced between them—mediator or entertainer, hard to say.

        Despite everything, Kira smiled. They had personalities, individual perspectives—Remedy's practical chemistry vs. Holloway's bureaucratic coordination—both trying to help in their own ways.

        She was starting to see them as people, not just obstacles. That was probably dangerous—getting attached to the alien plants keeping her alive through workplace safety protocols. But also inevitable.
      </text>
