        Kira asked, "Are there any other morning wellness tasks?"

        Holloway suggested, "Hydration status?"

        Kira gestured vaguely and said, "I should drink water—where's the…?"

        Scout bounced toward the spring feature—water flowed through shaped vines into a collection basin. Right—she'd seen it yesterday.

        Kira drank from cupped hands. The water was cool and clean, tasted faintly green—alien planet water processed through living architecture. Probably fine—hopefully.

        Not like she had options. Her stomach growled.

        Holloway said, "Oh—nutritional intake. Have you eaten since arrival?"

        Kira paused, "No—there wasn't really… time, or food."

        Several fruiting bodies exclaimed, "That's a significant oversight—humans require regular nutritional intake per biological maintenance protocols!"

        Kira said, "Yeah—we do. Is there… is there human-compatible food available?"

        ¶

        Holloway said carefully, "We'll need to conduct a dietary assessment—and file nutritional accommodation requests. This may take some time."

        Of course it would. Kira's stomach growled again—more urgently.

        Kira asked, "How much time?"

        Holloway said, "Standard dietary assessment protocol is approximately four hours—including forms, testing, and approval processes."

        Four hours—while hungry, after not eating since the crash—how long, a day and a half?

        Kira made herself say, "I understand—let's begin the dietary assessment process. I'm ready to provide nutritional requirements documentation."

        See? She was learning—phrase it in their framework. Work within the system. Even when her stomach was eating itself.

        Holloway said, "*Wonderful attitude!* I'll prepare the forms immediately!"

        Remedy tilted its head and observed, "Humans can actually survive several weeks without food—though subjective discomfort increases significantly. Interesting how biological maintenance panic starts long before actual decomposition risk. Just providing context—your body won't start breaking down vital tissues for at least another week or two."

        Kira muttered, "_Very_ comforting, thanks."

        Scout bounced anxiously and pressed against her leg. Kira reached down to touch the fuzzy surface and said, "It's okay—I can wait four hours."

        She had survived worse yesterday—workplace safety training, medical documentation while bleeding. This was just hungry paperwork.

        She could adapt to this. She was adapting, apparently.

        One absurd bureaucratic requirement at a time.
      </text>
